Reactive dyes get hydrolyzed in aqueous medium where the hydrolysis kinetics depends on the dye bath pH, temperature and time [43]. Also hydrolyzed dye molecules form micelles inside the dye bath in the form of dye molecule agglomerations. Particle size analysis of the dye bath reveals this by showing an increase in average particle size with time for both normal heating and ultra sound dyeing (Fig. 5
                        ). Polydispersity index value measured for these dye baths (Table 2
                        ) showed a uniform particle size distribution (PDI∼0.5–1) when ultra sonication method of dyeing is used. According to Fig. 5(a) ultra sound dye bath shows relatively low particle size of 310nm compared to normal heating dye bath of 510nm particle size during first 30min of dyeing period at 30°C. After 60min inside the dye bath, due to further hydrolysis of these dye molecules, in both systems, a further increase in the particle size was observed. The adsorption of the dye molecules on to the yarn surface is restricted after the aggregation. High energy water jet which produced during sonication is capable of breaking down these micelles and forming mono molecule dyes. Dye bath with ultra sound during first 30min and after 60min of dyeing shows a decrease in particle size dyed at all temperature range. During ultra sound dyeing, due to the de-agglomeration and better penetration of dye particles within the intra yarn structure of the fabric, allowed quick chemical interaction between dye and fibers which led to a better color strength of the fabric compared to normal heating dyeing.

Fig. 7
 shows the FT-IR spectra obtained for un-dyed cotton fabric, cotton fabrics dyed using normal heating and cotton fabrics dyed using ultra sonication at 30°C after 60min. Three spectra clearly show the functional groups available for cellulose. FT-IR spectra of ultra sound dyed fabric at 30°C (Fig. 7c) after washing shows absorption peaks at 1560cm−1 and 2360cm−1. Similar peaks were observed for cotton fabrics dyed using normal heating at 60°C after 60min of dyeing. The absorption at wave number 1560cm−1 corresponds to the amide bond (N–H) and 2360cm−1 corresponds to Azide bond (NN) present in the dye molecules. This shows dye molecules are capable of permanently attaching on fiber surface even after washing, when dyed with ultra sound at low temperature. Ultra sonication energy has led to formation of dye fiber interaction at low temperature. When use normal heating, dye fiber interaction has taken place at relatively higher temperature (60°C). FT-IR peaks obtained for cotton fabric dyed using different methods of dyeing are assigned in Table 2. According to these results, in the presence of ultra sound, absorption peaks attribute for NN bond of the dye molecule can be observed on cotton fabrics when dyed at 30°C, 40°C and 60°C. Ultra sound energy was able to de-agglomerate the dye particles and force the dye fiber interaction during the dyeing process without any effect from the temperature of the dye bath (see Table 3
).
